  "opinion": "As a 63-year-old hairdresser from Bari, I've seen a lot in my life, and social media is just another part of it that I use a few times a week to stay connected with clients and friends. Dealing with fake content on these platforms can be quite overwhelming, especially since I tend to worry a lot—my high neuroticism score means I often feel anxious about things that might not be true or could harm others. When I come across something suspicious online, like a sensational health tip or a dramatic news story, my first instinct is to pause and not share it immediately. I remember a time when a client showed me a post claiming a certain hair product was dangerous, and it caused a lot of unnecessary panic in our small community. I learned then that it's crucial to check sources, even if it takes a bit of effort. Since I'm creative, I sometimes use that to think of alternative ways to verify information, like asking trusted friends or looking up official websites. My moderate agreeableness makes me want to help others, so I gently remind people to be cautious without being confrontational. As a self-employed widow with one child, I value honesty and trust in my business and personal life, and fake content undermines that. I believe the best approach is to stay informed through reliable channels, limit my time on social media to avoid stress, and focus on real-world connections, like my yoga classes and classical music hobbies, which bring me peace. Ultimately, managing fake content is about being thoughtful and responsible, something I try to practice every day in my salon and online.",
